le="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">)</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">]</span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo MJXc-space3"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.151em; padding-bottom: 0.372em;">:</span></span> <span class="mjx-mrow MJXc-space3"><span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">[</span></span> <span class="mjx-texatom"><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.109em;">P</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">(</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.519em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">O</span></span> <span class="mjx-texatom"><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">|</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">B</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">)</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo MJXc-space2"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.225em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">×</span></span> <span class="mjx-texatom MJXc-space2"><span class="mjx-mrow"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.109em;">P</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">(</span></span> <span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">B</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">)</span></span></span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.593em;">]</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p><p>这如何应用于竞争性测验？我们正在努力寻找问题的答案 - 但我们每次只收到一个单词（实际上是一个音节！）的问题。逐字逐句地提出问题：这就是我们收到的证据。我们对答案可能是什么的想法，假设。</p><h4>校准</h4><p>除了不确定性的表征之外，信念形成和决策的另一个重要方面是<em>正确</em>处理不确定性。</p><p>通常如何实施这一点是<a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/tag/calibration"><em>校准</em>我们的不确定性</a>的概念。如果我们在某个命题中表达（或以隐含表达的方式行事）80% 的置信水平，那么如果 80% 的类似案例得到积极解决，我们就得到了校准。</p><p>这实际上比我们想象的更棘手、更哲学！什么是“类似案例”？那么小数量级的置信水平（例如 0.00001%）又如何呢？ - 当然，我们永远无法遇到或识别足够多的“类似案例”来确定我们是否已校准！我们是否必须开始寻求<em>反事实的可能结果</em>的概念（但愿上帝不允许）？我没有答案，据我所知，这些一方面是哲学中的开放问题（描述性的），另一方面是机器学习和统计学方面的开放性问题（规定性的）。</p><p>测验时，如果我对答案有 80% 的把握，我希望这对应于我大约 80% 的时间是正确的！否则我就会失去预期，要么因为我太自信而犯错（丢分），要么因为太晚而输给对方球队的某人。 <sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-5" id="fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-5">[5]</a></sup></p><h4>逻辑或计算的不确定性</h4><p>贝叶斯文献中存在一个大漏洞。实际上，这是整个统计文献中的一个大漏洞，只是在贝叶斯域中更明显，因为它更明确。</p><p>有时我们的不确定性是因为<em>我们还没有足够的时间去思考</em>。考虑 pi 的数字。 （想必您知道它们。如果不知道，我可以告诉您枚举它们的有效过程，完成后您可以回来。）假设我想知道百万分之一这样的数字。嗯，我知道到达那里所需的所有事实。它只能是十种（假设十进制）。我本身不需要做任何更多的“观察”来得出结论。但我仍然不知道答案。</p><p>作为一台自我反思的计算机并尝试做困难的事情的一个有趣的事情是，当你遇到<em>计算限制</em>时，你开始注意到 - 特别是像这样的那些并不总是显而易见的（或者为了简单而被忽略的）理论家最初几次涉足试图理清事物！这只是一个例子，其中将<em>时间限制</em><sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-6" id="fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-6">[6]</a></sup>视为有效计算过程的主要决定因素，从而产生了有趣的科学问题和见解。</p><p>考试的时候也是这样。我们大脑的单词联想、检索、评估和更新只能运行这么快——通常不如测验大师阅读问题的速度！</p><p>作为一个技术难题，理解这方面的不确定性引起了我的兴趣。我当然不太相信标准的永恒的不确定性观点。 MIRI 有一些伟大的工作开始解决这个问题，例如<a href="https://intelligence.org/files/QuestionsLogicalUncertainty.pdf">讨论逻辑不确定性</a>和<a href="https://intelligence.org/2016/09/12/new-paper-logical-induction/">逻辑（或 Garrabrant）归纳</a>。</p><h3>快速做这件事</h3><p>我们没有机会在每个问题音节之后暂停时间，拿出记事本，运行一些超级计算机评估，计算精确的贝叶斯后验，估计我们的队友和对手的可信度以及可能的嗡嗡声行为，等等。残酷的是，时间以每秒一秒的速度流逝，而测验大师却一直在进行测验。生活中也是如此！我们在现代生活中的决定通常可能不像面对面测验那样瞬间做出，但我们的不确定性（包括逻辑不确定性）和错误的成本同样真实<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-7" id="fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-7">[7]</a></sup> 。</p><p>在 UC 中练习和比赛带来的主要变化之一是，我从“具有广泛知识基础和缓慢心理检索的测验新手”变成了“具有广泛知识基础和稍慢的心理检索速度的测验菜鸟”。特别是我们团队中的一个人是一位经验丰富的测验者，并且是压哨技术的绝对大师！进入经验丰富的测验者的世界让我对所涉及的挑战感到赞赏。我不知道这些能力的概括性如何，但如果竞争性测验者（比我更有经验）总体上在不确定性下的校准决策和预测方面表现出色（或具有巨大潜力），我不会感到惊讶。</p><p>当然，也许我对此分析过度了：毕竟，也许常识测验大多归结为残酷的知识库检索。你要么知道，要么不知道！但我认为，面对面的竞争方面提出了快速近似校准估计的要求：有时你必须努力做到这一点，否则你的对手就会！我没想到会对它有如此深入的了解，但它让我对 UC 节目以及一般的面对面测验有了新的认识。</p><h3>但代价是什么？</h3><p>整个讨论回避了想要在有限证据的基础上拥有准确和校准信念的<em>原因</em>。当然，拥有准确的信念很有趣，甚至可能是美德之类的，但通常我们想要它们，因为它们<em>帮助我们做好事</em>。</p><p>这就提出了成本问题：如果我的信念融入到我的行动中，并且我的计算预算（总是）有限，那么我期望它能产生<em>多大的变化</em>就很重要。在大学挑战赛中，对于每个蜂鸣器问题，有六个结果，我为每个结果标明了粗略的净分数</p><ul><li>(-25) 失分，其他队伍获得积分</li><li>(-20) 其他队伍获得分数</li><li>(-5) 失分，其他队伍一无所获</li><li>(0) 没有人得到任何东西</li><li>(20) 获得积分</li><li>(25) 其他队失分，你得分</li></ul><p>（我们可能会发现，还有其他秘密选项，例如“（-1000）在国家电视台上说一些令人尴尬的事情”。）</p><p>我们对这些结果的期望取决于</p><ul><li>我们目前对答案的估计</li><li>我们对队友状态的估计</li><li>我们对对手状态的估计</li><li>（猜测问题多久结束）</li></ul><p>由于这些原因，当时间和/或决策计算资源稀缺时，对所有这些进行快速近似和深入检查是值得的。我觉得我自己的系统 1 通过练习慢慢地融入了其中的一些东西，我认为这是真正优秀的测验者与我们其他人的区别的很大一部分！</p><p>在某种程度上，这整件事与我作为行业数据科学家和软件工程师所做的许多工作模式匹配，这些工作与在线秘密拍卖有关：我们对队友和对手的状态的估计与他们的“出价”相对应”以及我们自己的估计，与我们对该项目的“真实评估”相对应。与测验一样，时间有限且计算限制占主导地位。在这些情况下，高吞吐量和快速的受限决策往往胜过缓慢而艰苦的审议。我什至有一种预感，我在那里发展的一些理论可能会转移！ - 特别是关于如何在不确定的市场环境中处理时间分布量的最优投标。但我对数学还没有玩够，我需要检查 NDA 涵盖的内容，所以我不会再详细说明。</p><p>您会发现我在下面做了一些节省时间的近似和反演，以及考虑成本，而不仅仅是信念更新。</p><h2>只要回答问题就可以了！</h2><p>好的，以对话的形式。请记住，这些都是诚实的但假设的（我不允许透露节目中的任何真实内容）。我部分但不完全地将样本偏向于我所了解的主题<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-8" id="fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-8">[8]</a></sup> 。</p><blockquote><p> <strong>Quizmaster (QM)</strong> ：什么个位数......</p><p> <strong>Oly (O)</strong> : P([0-9] 以外的任何值) = 0</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ...链接：硼元素，...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> ：硼是<span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="B"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em;">B</span></span></span></span></span></span> ，第 3 族，元素 5，质量 10（对，通常是？）[思考]</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> ：……第四个……</p><p> <strong>O</strong> ：必须是 5，质子数、基团数将是一个奇怪的选择，而且由于过渡元素、嗡嗡声时间，无论如何它都会受到争论......？</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> ：... 625 的根...</p><p><strong>奥</strong>：[嗡嗡声]5</p></blockquote><p>以及整个问题</p><blockquote><p>什么个位数联系在一起：元素硼、625 的四根、以及木星与太阳的位置？ (5)</p></blockquote><p>评论：还不错，如果我对校准更有信心的话，我可能会更早发出嗡嗡声。谁知道我的对手会不会如此谨慎……？如果我知道他们是等待类型，我可以休息一下并仔细检查 5 的四次方，只是为了真正确定，或者等待更多并数“我的真正简单方法”。</p><p>速度超级智能怎么样？我们可以想象他们不会遭受或有限的逻辑不确定性 - 实际上他们可以在每个音节后暂停。那么，“元素”将是一个大线索，他们可以预先计算从前十种化学元素到它们的质子数和质量数的映射。因为稳定的质量数不是唯一定义的，所以质子数已经得到了大部分后验，一旦说出“bor-”，实际上就只有一个可能的答案。</p><hr><blockquote><p> <strong>QM</strong> ：像短号……</p><p> <strong>O</strong> ：嗯，我在铜管乐队中演奏过很多次，这是铜管乐器短号还是其他乐器？ P（铜管乐器）= 0.7。也许是小号。 P（喇叭）= 0.4。我应该嗡嗡声吗？</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> ：...但是有一个稍微大一点的钟，...</p><p><strong>哦</strong>：‘铃’！一定是黄铜！ P(喇叭) = 0.7 [注意，为了遵循贝叶斯，这个值应该更低]但是呃，其他的是什么？短笛小号、女高音短号、...</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> ：...哪种乐器是英国铜管乐器的标准...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> ：……等等，它们都有<em>较小的</em>铃铛。思考</p><p><strong>QM</strong> ：……乐队，它的名字是德语</p><p><strong>O</strong> ：天翼种的号角！ [嗡嗡声] 弗鲁盖尔号角</p></blockquote><p>以及整个问题</p><blockquote><p>Resembling a cornet but having a slightly larger bell, which instrument is a standard in British brass bands, its name being the German for &#39;wing horn&#39;? (Flugelhorn)</p></blockquote><p> Review: My logical uncertainty and brain speed let me down here. But I got very lucky on actually having spent a lot of time in British brass bands. Handy coincidence. The speed superintelligence would have done better in my place, but only if it had niche knowledge of brass band instruments.</p><hr><blockquote><p> <strong>QM</strong> : Rayleigh-Taylor, ...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : [pure association] physics or maths stuff?</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ...Kelvin-Helmholtz and ...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Definitely physics! I&#39;ve heard of Rayleigh scattering, won&#39;t be Taylor polynomials, Kelvin did... temperature stuff? Helmholtz did a bit of everything. Acoustics?</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ...Rayleigh-Bénard are all types...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Rayleigh again! Scattering? But I can&#39;t confidently link the other names, and I haven&#39;t heard of these name pairings at all.</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ... of what general physical phenomenon, characterised by the unbounded growth of small disturbances?</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Oh, must be chaos! That&#39;s a general physical phenomenon. Question seems to be over, teammates haven&#39;t buzzed yet... [buzz] Chaos</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> (looking disappointed): I&#39;m afraid that&#39;s the wrong answer</p></blockquote><p> And the whole question</p><blockquote><p> Rayleigh-Taylor, Kelvin-Helmholtz and Rayleigh-Bénard are all types of what general physical phenomenon, characterised by the unbounded growth of small disturbances? (Instability)</p></blockquote><p> Ouch. If any of the other players had better physics breadth or recall, they&#39;d have certainly got it long before I failed to. In practice there&#39;s at least one of my teammates (cough Omer cough) who I&#39;d expect to get this question, or to have buzzed sooner with a guess than me! At least I didn&#39;t buzz early with a wrong answer.</p><hr><blockquote><p> <strong>QM</strong> : Following the example of the Cadbury brothers&#39; model...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Ooh, I did my undergrad in Birmingham and I remember some history about this</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ... at Bourneville, which manufacturer and philanthropist...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : OK, Bourneville was a constructed model village for confectionary workers, designed to offer better quality of life - getting distracted. It&#39;s probably another confectioner. Rowntree, Fry, ...? P(something I didn&#39;t think of) = 0.3</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ...developed the model village of New Earswick, north east of York?</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : My Granny lived in York and told me this! Pretty sure it was Rowntree. Confidence? Question seems over, time to [buzz]. Rowntree.</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : Can I ask which Rowntree...?</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Uhhhh. [I really should have read that fun Chocolate Wars book they gave us at undergrad induction. Pick a common early C20 businessman&#39;s name.] John?</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : I&#39;m afraid that&#39;s the wrong answer</p></blockquote><p> And the whole question</p><blockquote><p> Following the example of the Cadbury brothers&#39; model at Bourneville, which manufacturer and philanthropist developed the model village of New Earswick, north east of York? (Joseph Rowntree (1836-1926; not to be confused with his son, Seebohm Rowntree))</p></blockquote><p> Review: well, that seems harsh. I&#39;m not sure actually on the real show if they&#39;d have given this or not. This was basically a case of fact retrieval, though it illustrates the important issue of allocating probability/credence to &#39;something I didn&#39;t think of yet&#39;.</p><hr><blockquote><p> <strong>QM</strong> : Which art gallery...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : P(art gallery) = 1. I know hardly any, thankfully my teammates might know a few more. I remember visiting the Tate and Tate Modern as a kid. P(something I&#39;ve never heard of) = 0.8.</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ...links How It Is by Miroslaw Balka, Shibboleth by Doris Salcedo, ...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Sound quite modern. P(modern) = 0.8</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ... Embankment by Rachel Whiteread, Marsyas by Anish Kapoor ...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Confidently all modern</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ... and The Weather Project by Olafur Eliasson?</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Wait, that sounds familiar. It might actually be Tate Modern. Question&#39;s over. [buzz] Tate Modern</p></blockquote><p> And the whole question</p><blockquote><p> Which art gallery links How It Is by Miroslaw Balka, Shibboleth by Doris Salcedo, Embankment by Rachel Whiteread, Marsyas by Anish Kapoor and The Weather Project by Olafur Eliasson? (Tate Modern)</p></blockquote><p> Review: I got very lucky here (as I said, I biased my sample a bit <sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-8" id="fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-8:1">[8:1]</a></sup> ). In practice, someone else would probably have beaten me to it by a long shot, hopefully someone on my team!</p><hr><blockquote><p> <strong>QM</strong> : In 2010, which tennis player ...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Oh no, sport facts. Hopefully Daniel is on it. Federer? Djokovic? Williams? Nadal? Murray?</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ... became the seventh player to win all four Grand Slam tournaments when he defeated Novak Djokovic in the US Open men&#39;s final?</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Yep, no idea. P(Federer or Nadal or Murray) = 0.3. Strictly, if alone, I ought to buzz and guess <em>something</em> now that the question has finished. But surely a teammate has a better guess than me?</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : Anyone? Anyone going to buzz?</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : I really should buzz and guess. But besides getting answer right, my utility function also includes not putting myself forward embarrassingly wrongly on TV. P(wrong) = 0.9.</p></blockquote><p> And the whole question</p><blockquote><p> In 2010, which tennis player became the seventh player to win all four Grand Slam tournaments when he defeated Novak Djokovic in the US Open men&#39;s final? (Rafael Nadal)</p></blockquote><p> Review: This awkward silence actually happens, quite rarely, but sometimes, on the show. I assume this can only be when everyone involved has a similar thought process to me at the end. A superintelligence optimised exclusively to value University Challenge performance might not have similar compunctions, but there&#39;s also no knowing what instrumental strategies it might pursue. Maybe embarrassment or some analogue would actually play a part there.</p><hr><blockquote><p> <strong>QM</strong> : &#39;Chain&#39;, &#39;double treble&#39;, &#39;reverse half double&#39;...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Sport? &#39;treble&#39; is a musical clef? Gymnastics?</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ... and &#39;slip stitch&#39; ...</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : Oh, knitting or something? I remember something about this.</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : ... are all terms used in which handicraft</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : It has to be knitting, right? Can I afford to wait? [buzz] Knitting</p><p> <strong>QM</strong> : I&#39;m afraid that&#39;s the wrong answer and you lose five points. ...in which handicraft, whose name is a diminutive for the French word for &#39;hook&#39;?</p><p> <strong>O</strong> : [fuming] Should have waited! It&#39;s got to be crochet.</p></blockquote><p> And the full question</p><blockquote><p> &#39;Chain&#39;, &#39;double treble&#39;, &#39;reverse half double&#39; and &#39;slip stitch&#39; are all terms used in which handicraft, whose name is a diminutive of the French word for &#39;hook&#39;? (Crochet (not knitting or embroidery))</p></blockquote><p> Review: I&#39;d have thought this would be an acceptable error, but then, for my sins, I don&#39;t know much about the fine distinctions between wool-based handicrafts. Alas. This is one where the competitive uncertainty bit me, my model of the opponents&#39; lack of buzzing interpreting it as over-caution (therefore we&#39;re in a race and I&#39;d better not waste more time thinking) rather than appropriate caution (therefore I&#39;d better think harder to generate alternative hypotheses in case). A speed SI version of me would have generated at least &#39;crochet&#39; as an alternative, and, I expect, waited until &#39;name is a diminutive&#39; which would be enough evidence to be confident.</p><h2> Takeaways</h2><p> This post is already far too long. You can tune in on 2023-09-04 20:30 UK time on BBC 2 or <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m001q8bf">watch or catch up online</a> if you want to see me and my team in action!</p><p> Quizzing (and more importantly the practice matches and friendlies) gave me a fresh appreciation for various decision-making concerns, theoretical and practical. Plus, it was a great laugh and a chance to meet some really intriguing and friendly people, here in Oxford as well as from other teams.</p><p> Uncertainty is powerful! Calibration is a slightly elusive concept, but an important part of using uncertainty appropriately.</p><p> <em>Logical</em> uncertainty is a fascinating and under-studied phenomenon - especially in time- or compute-constrained settings!</p><p> As well as getting things right, we often need to accept some tradeoff for getting things wrong in order to free up decision-making and acting resources for other uses. When you&#39;re in a head-to-head time-based competition, this bites <em>hard</em> .</p><p> Finally, decision-making is, ultimately, about <em>value</em> . If my belief doesn&#39;t make a value-difference by changing my behaviour, then I might better pay attention to other beliefs which do, even at the expense of the first belief being true. Again this only bites in a constrained context: whether constrained by evidence (for factual uncertainty) or by compute (for logical uncertainty). Since there are <em>so many</em> things we are terribly clueless about, this actually applies in practice all the time.</p><p> Quizzing is fun, and I haven&#39;t even got round to mentioning the arcane art of quiz- <em>writing</em> . A peek behind the scenes at how those particular sausages are made was also illuminating. Were it possible, quiz- and puzzle-setters have gone up even further in my estimations.</p><p> If you&#39;re a quizzer or a quiz-setter (whether with more or less experience than me), I&#39;d love to hear if any of this resonated with you, and about your own reflections on the art of quizzing and decision-making! </p><hr class="footnotes-sep"><section class="footnotes"><ol class="footnotes-list"><li id="fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-1" class="footnote-item"><p> I&#39;ve enjoyed as many pub quizzes as the next Brit but that&#39;s about as far as it goes <a href="#fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-1" class="footnote-backref">↩︎</a></p></li><li id="fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-2" class="footnote-item"><p> You win 10 points for a correct answer, whether early or not (hence &#39;Starter for 10&#39;), and you lose 5 for an interruption and an incorrect answer. An incorrect answer after the end of the question gets nothing. There are also non-buzzer questions where teams can confer, for bonus points. <a href="#fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-2" class="footnote-backref">↩︎</a></p></li><li id="fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-3" class="footnote-item"><p> OK, when I said &#39;literature&#39; I meant &#39;scientific literature&#39; ie papers and textbooks, but actually this sentence applies to some of my favourite <em>actual</em> literature too: Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality, for example. <a href="#fnref-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-3" class="footnote-backref">↩︎</a></p></li><li id="fn-HADF3ByWnoTYEzsgd-4" class="footnote-item"><p> I&#39;ve used my favoured formulation of Bayes&#39; Rule here where it&#39;s all about odds (ratios of probabilities/likelihoods). I think it&#39;s a historical accident that Bayes usually gets introduced in less obvious ways and then forgotten.</p><p> You&#39;ll often see credences represented as probabilities <span class="mjpage"><span class="mjx-chtml"><span class="mjx-math" aria-label="P(\cdot)"><span class="mjx-mrow" aria-hidden="true"><span class="mjx-mi"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-math-I" style="padding-top: 0.446em; padding-bottom: 0.298em; padding-right: 0.109em;">P</span></span> <span class="mjx-mo"><span class="mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R" style="padding-top: 0.446e